<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-688-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 688 234.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  July 27 1990 n1477* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US defence contractors tread on toes of contract manufacturers inbid for work.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Defense ContractsBudgetingStrategic PlanningReorganizationContractorsManufacturersComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>US DEFENCE CONTRACTORS TREAD ON TOES OF CONTRACTandM;MANUFACTURERS IN BID FOR WORKandM;Not surprisingly, the easing of the Cold War and subsequent cutting ofmilitary budgets is taking its toll on defence manufacturers.andP;  But attemptsto boost falling revenues are having a domino effect, and other sectors ofthe computer industry have noticed that defence manufacturers are becomingmore prominent in the world of contract manufacturing.andP;  Yet, as ElectronicNews points out, if Department of Defense companies are to diversifysuccessfully, they will have to adjust to a culture that doesn't endorseoverruns and escalating costs.andP;  Another factor that could hinder defencecontractors is the rapid rate of turnaround in the industrial market,something they are not accustomed to.andP;  Some newcomers acknowledge thequestion mark over their competitiveness, and admit that they probablycouldn't match established players in producing high-volume commercialboards.andP;  Nonetheless, there are opportunities to win contracts that requiredesign and engineering expertise, especially from firms that want to reducein-house efforts.andP;  Companies willing to turn a hand to contract manufacturinginclude Norden Systems, Martin Marietta, and IBM's Federal Sector division.andO;All have spare capacity and claim to have keen design and engineering skillsthat could be applied outside the military.andO;</TEXT></DOC>